<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/936D002F-A8D1-4A93-AE5D-825ED0903D8D"><gtr:id>936D002F-A8D1-4A93-AE5D-825ED0903D8D</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Nottingham</gtr:name><gtr:department>Sch of Economics</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Park</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Nottingham</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Nottinghamshire</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>NG7 2RD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East Midlands</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/936D002F-A8D1-4A93-AE5D-825ED0903D8D"><gtr:id>936D002F-A8D1-4A93-AE5D-825ED0903D8D</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Nottingham</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Park</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Nottingham</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Nottinghamshire</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>NG7 2RD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East Midlands</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/EB027124-F456-44FB-8011-804F402AB6DC"><gtr:id>EB027124-F456-44FB-8011-804F402AB6DC</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Arijit</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Mukherjee</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-072-27-0040"><gtr:id>D4BB2FE7-7A38-496A-9B7A-19E57DCA4B2E</gtr:id><gtr:title>Reform, Asymmetric Organisation and Development: Theory and Practices of Formal-Informal Sector Linkages in India</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-072-27-0040</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This study seeks to enquire:&lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>the causes of organisational shifting from independent to tied, and its implication on the survival of small and marginal production units at the informal sector&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>the implication of the emergence of big traders into retail business on the suppliers. &lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>

&lt;p>Since early 1990s India moved from restrictive policy regime towards more liberal framework, which may have significant impact on the organisation of formal and informal sector firms in India. It is observed that the informal firms are specialised on particular divisions of work and are getting tied to the master under contractual relation. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The buyer-seller relationship is another important issue in today's world. The monopsony power of the big business houses may make the small suppliers worse off. However, a specialised supplier may also have significant bargaining power in the formation of supplier price. Moreover entry of new buyers may raise the competitiveness in buyer's market and may affect a buyer's preference for tying up with a supplier in order to reduce market uncertainty or transaction costs.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>We want to analyse these issues by developing new theoretical models, and also intend to test empirically if possible.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>5200</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>We published two papers from this project.

In our paper in Labour Economics we show the effects of international trade cost reduction in the presence of an import-competing firm's strategic output allocation
between formal in-house production and subcontracting to the informal sector.

If the import-competing firm sells only in the domestic country, we show that a trade cost reduction increases in-house unionised wage and employment but decreases informal production and profit of the import-competing firm. While it makes the consumers better off, the effect on the importing country's welfare is ambiguous effect.

In the case of a two-way trade, where the import-competing firm also sells in the foreign country, if the markets are symmetric and segmented, the effects on the above-mentioned importing country are as follows: a symmetric trade cost reduction decreases the unionised wage and employment, increases informal production and consumer surplus and creates an ambiguous effect on the profit of its firm.

Thus, this paper sheds light on the distributional effects of a trade cost reduction and suggests that the possibility of output allocation between the formal and informal sectors generates significantly different outcomes compared to the situation where the firms produce in-house only.

In our paper in International Review of Economics and Finance we show how good economic governance in the importing country, reducing domestic marketing and distribution costs, affects inward foreign direct investment and welfare of the importing country.

We show that the effect of good governance is ambiguous on
the welfare of the importing country, and it depends on the cost difference between the firms, international transportation cost and the extent of cost reduction on the foreign and domestic firms. Our analysis reveals that an importing country may need complementary foreign direct investment policies along with good governance in order to maintain foreign direct investment flows and higher welfare on the country.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Our findings would be useful for academics, managers and policy makers.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>C1A504E4-79A0-4D2C-8114-4D8C28AC5284</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>542bf92a776355.89669834</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Manufacturing, including Industrial Biotechology</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>97224BB1-8A89-400B-BEC8-CE0BCBC8FE45</gtr:id><gtr:title>Governance, foreign direct investment and domestic welfare</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>International Review of Economics &amp; Finance</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/e1d061598da88017d6376d0c53d9c5ce"><gtr:id>e1d061598da88017d6376d0c53d9c5ce</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Maiti D</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2013-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cfb1fb1d0760fe</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>DB770E09-A366-4239-96AB-9FAD1CE5497D</gtr:id><gtr:title>Trade cost reduction, subcontracting and unionised wage</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Labour Economics</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/c5237585ce6a5e19cd203cb4d10fc6ff"><gtr:id>c5237585ce6a5e19cd203cb4d10fc6ff</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Maiti Dibyendu</gtr:otherNam